11 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
12 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
13 Article – Real Property
14 8–208.
15 (c) (1) IN THIS SUBSECTION, “OFFICE” MEANS THE OFFICE OF TENANT
16 AND LANDLORD AFFAIRS IN THE DEPARTMENT OF HOUSING AND COMMUNITY
17 DEVELOPMENT.
18 (2) A lease shall include:
19 [(1)] (I) A statement that the premises will be made available in a
20 condition permitting habitation, with reasonable safety, if that is the agreement, or if that
21 is not the agreement, a statement of the agreement concerning the condition of the
22 premises;
23 [(2)] (II) The landlord’s and the tenant’s specific obligations as to heat,
24 gas, electricity, water, and repair of the premises;
25 [(3)] (III) A receipt for the security deposit as specified in § 8–203.1 of this
26 subtitle; and
27 [(4)] (IV) A copy of the most current version of the Maryland Tenants’ Bill
28 of Rights published by the Office [of Tenant and Landlord Affairs in the Department of
29 Housing and Community Development].
30 (3) (I) THIS PARAGRAPH APPLIES ONLY IN A COUNTY THAT HAS
31 ADOPTED A LOCAL LAW OR ORDINANCE IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 8–402.3 OF THIS
32 TITLE.
33 (II) A LEASE OR LEASE RENEWAL SHALL INCLUDE NOTICE
34 STATING WHETHER THE LANDLORD IS SUBJECT TO THE LOCAL GOOD CAUSE

HOUSE BILL 774 3
1 STATUTE OR ORDINANCE OF THE COUNTY IN WHICH A RESIDENTIAL RENTAL UNIT IS
2 LOCATED.
3 (III) A LANDLORD STATING IN A NOTICE UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH
4 (II) OF THIS PARAGRAPH THAT THE LOCAL GOOD CAUSE PROVISIONS OF THE
5 COUNTY DO NOT APPLY TO THE LANDLORD SHALL PROVIDE THE TENANT WITH THE
6 FOLLOWING INFORMATION ON A FORM PRESCRIBED BY THE OFFICE:
7 1. THE FULL LEGAL NAME OF EACH INDIVIDUAL AND
8 THE BUSINESS NAME OF EACH ENTITY WITH DIRECT OR INDIRECT OWNERSHIP OR
9 MEMBERSHIP INTEREST IN THE RESIDENTIAL RENTAL UNIT;
10 2. THE NUMBER OF RESIDENTIAL RENTAL UNITS IN THE
11 STATE OWNED BY EACH INDIVIDUAL OR ENTITY IDENTIFIED UNDER ITEM 1 OF THIS
12 SUBPARAGRAPH, INCLUDING THE ADDRESS OF EACH RESIDENTIAL RENTAL UNIT
13 IDENTIFIED; AND
14 3. ANY OTHER INFORMATION REQUIRED BY THE
15 OFFICE.
16 (IV) AN INDIVIDUAL OR ENTITY HAS AN INTEREST IN A
17 RESIDENTIAL RENTAL UNIT UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (III) OF THIS PARAGRAPH IF
18 THE INDIVIDUAL OR ENTITY HAS A DIRECT OR INDIRECT OWNERSHIP OR
19 MEMBERSHIP INTEREST IN ANY ENTITY THAT HAS A DIRECT OR INDIRECT
20 OWNERSHIP OR MEMBERSHIP INTEREST IN THE RENTAL UNIT.
21 (V) IF A LANDLORD BECOMES SUBJECT TO A LOCAL GOOD
22 CAUSE LAW OR ORDINANCE, THE LANDLORD SHALL PROVIDE TIMELY WRITTEN
23 NOTICE TO ALL TENANTS OF THE LANDLORD IN THE COUNTY IN WHICH THE GOOD
24 CAUSE REQUIREMENTS APPLY, INCLUDING ANY TENANT HOLDING OVER UNDER §
25 8–402 OF THIS TITLE.
26 (VI) 1. THE OFFICE SHALL DEVELOP AND MAKE PUBLICLY
27 AVAILABLE A DISCLOSURE FORM FOR USE BY A LANDLORD UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH
28 (III) OF THIS PARAGRAPH.
29 2. THE OFFICE MAY ADOPT REGULATIONS TO CARRY
30 OUT THIS PARAGRAPH.
31 8–402.
32 (c) (1) This subsection applies to all cases of tenancies at the expiration of a
33 stated term, tenancies from year to year, tenancies from month to month, and tenancies
34 from week to week.

4 HOUSE BILL 774
1 (2) Except as provided in paragraphs (3) and (4) of this subsection, AND
2 SUBJECT TO ANY LOCAL REQUIREMENT ADOPTED IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 8–402.3
3 OF THIS SUBTITLE, a landlord shall provide written notice of the intent to terminate a
4 tenancy:
5 (i) If the parties have a written lease for a stated term in excess of
6 1 week or a tenancy from month to month, 60 days before the expiration of the tenancy;
7 (ii) In the case of tenancies from year to year, including tobacco farm
8 tenancies from year to year but excluding all other farm tenancies from year to year, 90
9 days before the expiration of the current year of the tenancy;
10 (iii) In the case of tenancies from year to year for all other farm
11 tenancies, 180 days before the expiration of the current year of the tenancy; and
12 (iv) In the case of tenancies from week to week:
13 1. If the parties have a written lease, 7 days before the
14 expiration of the tenancy; or
15 2. If the parties do not have a written lease, 21 days before
16 the expiration of the tenancy.
17 (d) Unless stated otherwise in the written lease and initialed by the tenant, when
18 a landlord consents to a holdover tenant remaining on the premises, the holdover tenant
19 becomes a periodic week–to–week tenant if the tenant was a week–to–week tenant before
20 the tenant’s holding over, and a periodic month–to–month tenant in all other cases.
21 (E) (1) IN THIS SUBSECTION, “OFFICE” MEANS THE OFFICE OF TENANT
22 AND LANDLORD AFFAIRS IN THE DEPARTMENT OF HOUSING AND COMMUNITY
23 DEVELOPMENT.
24 (2) THIS SUBSECTION APPLIES ONLY IN A COUNTY THAT HAS
25 ADOPTED A LOCAL LAW OR ORDINANCE IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 8–402.3 OF THIS
26 SUBTITLE.
27 (3) (I) PRIOR TO OR CONTEMPORANEOUSLY WITH NOTICE
28 REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION, A LANDLORD SHALL USE THE
29 FORM DEVELOPED BY THE OFFICE TO PROVIDE WRITTEN NOTICE BY FIRST–CLASS
30 MAIL WITH A CERTIFICATE OF MAILING TO A TENANT STATING:
31 1. THE GOOD CAUSE FOR THE NONRENEWAL OF THE
32 LEASE OR THE TERMINATION OF THE HOLDOVER TENANCY; OR

HOUSE BILL 774 5
1 2. THAT THE LANDLORD IS NOT SUBJECT TO THE LOCAL
2 GOOD CAUSE REQUIREMENTS ESTABLISHED IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 8–402.3 OF
3 THIS SUBTITLE.
4 (II) THE OFFICE SHALL DEVELOP AND MAKE PUBLICLY
5 AVAILABLE A FORM FOR THE NOTICE UNDER THIS PARAGRAPH.
6 (4) (I) A COMPLAINT FILED UNDER THIS SECTION SHALL STATE
7 ONE OF THE FOLLOWING:
8 1. THE GOOD CAUSE FOR THE NONRENEWAL OF THE
9 LEASE OR THE TERMINATION OF THE HOLDOVER TENANCY; OR
10 2. THAT THE LANDLORD IS NOT SUBJECT TO THE LOCAL
11 GOOD CAUSE REQUIREMENTS ADOPTED IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 8–402.3 OF THIS
12 SUBTITLE.
13 (II) A LANDLORD SHALL PLEAD SPECIFIC FACTS IN THE
14 COMPLAINT TO PROVE THE STATEMENTS MADE UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS
15 PARAGRAPH BY A PREPONDERANCE OF THE EVIDENCE.
16 (III) 1. IF A LANDLORD CLAIMS IN THE STATEMENT THAT THE
17 LANDLORD IS NOT SUBJECT TO THE LOCAL GOOD CAUSE REQUIREMENTS UNDER §
18 8–402.3(B) OF THIS SUBTITLE, THE LANDLORD SHALL INCLUDE A CURRENT
19 DISCLOSURE FORM AS PROVIDED IN § 8–208(C)(3)(III) OF THIS TITLE WITH THE
20 COMPLAINT.
21 2. AN INDIVIDUAL THAT IS IDENTIFIED IN THE
22 DISCLOSURE FORM AS HAVING A DIRECT OR INDIRECT OWNERSHIP INTEREST IN
23 THE RESIDENTIAL RENTAL UNIT OF THE LANDLORD, OR THAT INDIVIDUAL’S
24 DESIGNEE, SHALL SUBMIT AN AFFIDAVIT WITH THE COMPLAINT THAT CERTIFIES
25 THE DISCLOSURE FORM IS TRUE AND COMPLETE.
26 3. IF A CURRENT DISCLOSURE FORM AND AFFIDAVIT
27 ARE NOT SUBMITTED WITH THE COMPLAINT, THE LANDLORD SHALL BE SUBJECT TO
28 THE LOCAL GOOD CAUSE REQUIREMENTS OF THE COUNTY FOR THAT ACTION.
29 8–402.3.
30 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “HOLDOVER TENANCY” MEANS A TENANCY
31 ESTABLISHED UNDER § 8–402(D) OF THIS SUBTITLE.
32 (B) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, A COUNTY
33 MAY ADOPT, BY LOCAL LAW OR ORDINANCE, PROVISIONS THAT PROHIBIT A

6 HOUSE BILL 774
1 LANDLORD FROM FAILING TO RENEW A LEASE DURING THE LEASE PERIOD OR
2 SEEKING TO TERMINATE A HOLDOVER TENANCY WITHOUT GOOD CAUSE.
3 (2) EACH OF THE FOLLOWING GROUNDS SHALL CONSTITUTE GOOD
4 CAUSE IN A LOCAL LAW OR ORDINANCE ADOPTED UNDER THIS SECTION:
5 (I) A TENANT COMMITTING A SUBSTANTIAL BREACH OF THE
6 LEASE OR CAUSING SUBSTANTIAL DAMAGE TO THE LEASED PREMISES OR ANOTHER
7 AREA OF THE PROPERTY AND, AFTER RECEIVING NOTICE TO CURE OR CORRECT THE
8 BREACH OR PAY THE REASONABLE COST OF REPAIRING THE DAMAGE, FAILING TO
9 COMPLY WITHIN 14 DAYS;
10 (II) A TENANT ENGAGING IN ROUTINE DISORDERLY CONDUCT
11 THAT DISTURBS THE PEACE AND QUIET OF OTHER TENANTS;
12 (III) A TENANT ENGAGING IN ILLEGAL ACTIVITY ON THE LEASED
13 PREMISES, ANOTHER AREA OF THE PROPERTY, OR A PUBLIC RIGHT–OF–WAY
14 ABUTTING THE LEASED PREMISES;
15 (IV) A TENANT, WITHOUT REASONABLE CAUSE, REFUSING TO
16 GRANT THE LANDLORD ACCESS TO THE LEASED PREMISES FOR THE PURPOSE OF
17 MAKING REPAIRS OR IMPROVEMENTS OR INSPECTING THE LEASED PREMISES, OR
18 AS OTHERWISE AUTHORIZED UNDER THE RESIDENTIAL LEASE OR APPLICABLE LAW;
19 (V) A HOLDOVER TENANT FAILING TO ACCEPT A LANDLORD’S
20 OFFER OF A NEW LEASE AGREEMENT FOR A TERM OF AT LEAST 1 MONTH BUT NOT
21 LONGER THAN THE TERM OF THE LEASE AGREEMENT EFFECTIVE IMMEDIATELY
22 BEFORE THE HOLDOVER TENANCY WITHIN 1 MONTH AFTER THE LANDLORD MAKES
23 THE OFFER OR A GREATER PERIOD OF TIME AS OTHERWISE ESTABLISHED BY LAW;
24 (VI) A TENANT REPEATEDLY COMMITTING MINOR VIOLATIONS
25 OF THE LEASE THAT:
26 1. DISRUPT THE LIVABILITY OF THE LEASED PREMISES;
27 2. INTERFERE WITH THE MANAGEMENT OF THE
28 PROPERTY; OR
29 3. HAVE AN ADVERSE FINANCIAL IMPACT ON THE
30 PROPERTY;
31 (VII) A TENANT HABITUALLY FAILING TO PAY RENT WHEN DUE,
32 IF THE TENANT HAS BEEN NOTIFIED BY THE LANDLORD IN WRITING THAT THE RENT
33 IS MORE THAN 10 DAYS LATE AT LEAST FOUR TIMES IN A 12–MONTH PERIOD;

HOUSE BILL 774 7
1 (VIII) A LANDLORD, IN GOOD FAITH, SEEKING TO RECOVER
2 POSSESSION OF THE LEASED PREMISES FOR USE BY THE LANDLORD OR THE
3 LANDLORD’S:
4 1. SPOUSE;
5 2. CHILD OR STEPCHILD;
6 3. PARENT OR STEPPARENT;
7 4. GRANDPARENT;
8 5. SIBLING;
9 6. MOTHER–IN–LAW OR FATHER–IN–LAW;
10 7. DAUGHTER–IN–LAW OR SON–IN–LAW;
11 8. GRANDCHILD; OR
12 9. AUNT OR UNCLE;
13 (IX) A LANDLORD, AFTER HAVING OBTAINED ALL NECESSARY
14 PERMITS, SEEKING TO UNDERTAKE SUBSTANTIAL REPAIRS OR RENOVATIONS THAT
15 CANNOT BE COMPLETED WHILE THE LEASED PREMISES ARE OCCUPIED; AND
16 (X) A LANDLORD, IN GOOD FAITH, SEEKING TO REMOVE THE
17 LEASED PREMISES FOR AT LEAST 1 YEAR FROM THE RENTAL MARKET; AND
18 (XI) A TENANT’S OCCUPANCY IS CONDITIONED ON EMPLOYMENT
19 ON THE PROPERTY AND THE EMPLOYMENT RELATIONSHIP IS TERMINATED.
20 (3) A COUNTY MAY NOT ADOPT ADDITIONAL OR ALTERNATIVE
21 GROUNDS FOR GOOD CAUSE BY LOCAL LAW OR ORDINANCE.
22 (C) A LOCAL LAW OR ORDINANCE ADOPTED BY A COUNTY UNDER THIS
23 SECTION:
24 (1) SHALL APPLY ONLY TO A LANDLORD THAT OWNS SIX OR MORE
25 RESIDENTIAL RENTAL UNITS IN THE STATE, INCLUDING ANY RESIDENTIAL RENTAL
26 UNITS THAT THE LANDLORD OWNS OR CONTROLS:
27 (I) IN WHOLE OR IN PART;

8 HOUSE BILL 774
1 (II) DIRECTLY OR INDIRECTLY; OR
2 (III) THROUGH ONE OR MORE LEGAL ENTITIES; AND
3 (2) MAY NOT:
4 (I) APPLY TO AN:
5 1. A SHORT–TERM RENTAL UNIT, AS DEFINED BY THE
6 LOCAL JURISDICTION; OR
7 2. AN OWNER–OCCUPIED RESIDENTIAL RENTAL UNIT;
8 (II) REQUIRE A LANDLORD TO DEMONSTRATE GOOD CAUSE IF A
9 TENANT PROVIDES NOTICE TO THE LANDLORD THAT EXPRESSES THE TENANT’S
10 INTENT NOT TO RENEW THE LEASE OR CONTINUE WITH THE HOLDOVER TENANCY;
11 OR
12 (III) CONFLICT WITH THE NOTICE REQUIREMENTS OF § 8–402(C)
13 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
14 (D) A LOCAL LAW OR ORDINANCE ADOPTED BY A COUNTY UNDER THIS
15 SECTION SHALL APPLY UNIFORMLY THROUGHOUT THE COUNTY, INCLUDING IN
16 MUNICIPALITIES.
17 (E) (1) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION,
18 FOR PURPOSES OF ESTABLISHING THE NUMBER OF UNITS OWNED BY A LANDLORD
19 TO DETERMINE THE APPLICABILITY OF A LOCAL LAW OR ORDINANCE ADOPTED IN
20 ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SECTION, ANY RESIDENTIAL RENTAL UNIT IN THE STATE
21 OWNED BY AN INDIVIDUAL OR ENTITY THAT HAS DIRECT OR INDIRECT OWNERSHIP
22 OR MEMBERSHIP INTEREST IN THE LANDLORD SHALL BE CONSIDERED A UNIT
23 OWNED BY THE LANDLORD.
24 (2) AN INDIVIDUAL OR ENTITY DOES NOT HAVE OWNERSHIP OR
25 MEMBERSHIP INTEREST IN A LANDLORD IF THE INDIVIDUAL’S OR ENTITY’S
26 INTEREST IN THE LANDLORD IS IN THE NATURE OF A NONCONTROLLING INTEREST
27 IN A PUBLICLY TRADED CORPORATION, TRUST, MUTUAL FUND, OR SIMILAR
28 INVESTMENT VEHICLE.
29 (F) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, NOTHING IN
30 THIS SECTION MAY BE INTERPRETED TO ALTER THE RIGHTS OF A LANDLORD THAT
31 SEEKS RELIEF UNDER THIS SUBTITLE.

HOUSE BILL 774 9
1 (2) A LANDLORD IN A COUNTY THAT HAS ADOPTED A LOCAL LAW OR
2 ORDINANCE UNDER THIS SUBSECTION MAY SEEK RELIEF UNDER § 8–402 OF THIS
3 SUBTITLE ONLY AFTER DECLINING TO ENTER INTO A NEW LEASE OR TO CONTINUE A
4 HOLDOVER TENANCY IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE PROVISIONS OF THE LOCAL LAW
5 OR ORDINANCE.
6 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
7 October 1, 2026.
